'''Rex Grossman''' (born [[August 23]], [[1980]]) is a [[quarterback]] for the [[Chicago Bears]] of the [[National Football League]]. An [[Indiana]] native, Grossman graduated from [[Bloomington High School South]] and attended the [[University of Florida]] on an [[athletic scholarship]].<ref>CBS Chicago, [http://cbs2chicago.com/sports/local_story_026205644.html Rex Grossman's Family Talks About  His Success] Retrieved on [[February 24]], [[2007]]</ref> He led the [[Florida Gators]] to two championship games, and was the [[runner-up]] for the 2001 [[Heisman Trophy]].<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Gators">University of Florida Athletics, [http://www.gatorzone.com/football/bios.php?year=2002&bio=grossman.html University of Florida Athletics: Rex Grossman] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> 

Grossman began his professional career with the [[Chicago Bears]] as the twenty-second overall selection in the [[2003 NFL Draft]], but spent most of his first three seasons sidelined with injures.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> He completed his first full season in [[2006 Chicago Bears season|2006]], leading the Bears to a [[NFC Championship|National Football Conference Championship]], and helping the team score the second most points in the league.<ref>SNY.tv, [http://www.sny.tv/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070123&content_id=1420023&oid=35007_f&vkey=14 By the Numbers: The Super Bowl] Retrieved on [[April 3]], [[2007]]</ref> 

==Early life==
Rex Grossman was born in [[Bloomington, Indiana]] to Daniel and Maureen Grossman. Under the motivation and guidance of his father, Grossman began to play football at an early age in [[grade school]]. He originally started his football career as a [[running back]]. Despite his success as a running back, Grossman<U+2019>s mother asked his coach to convert him to a quarterback, while he was in the sixth grade.<ref name="Grossman_SunTimes">Chicago Suntimes, [http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4155/is_20031214/ai_n12519557 BEARS' RX: REX Grossman has Spent a Lifetime BEING GROOMED FOR] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref>

He attended [[Bloomington High School South|Bloomington South High School]], where he threw 97 touchdowns for 7,518 yards.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Grossman threw 44 touchdown passes during his senior year, including a game where he threw six and two games where he threw four. His senior season reached its pinnacle on [[November 28]], [[1998]], when he led his team to a 34-14 5A championship title over [[Homestead High School (Fort Wayne, Indiana)|Homestead High School]]. Grossman threw five touchdowns for 216 yards, setting a state record for most touchdowns thrown in a championship game.<ref>IHSAA.org, [http://www.ihsaa.org/b-football/98Class5AFinals.html 1998 IHSAA State Finals] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> 

Grossman received national recognition as the 1998 Indiana Player-of-the-Year by ''[[USA Today]]'', and was ranked among the top fifteen players in the nation by the National Recruiting Advisor.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> ''Parade Magazine'' also named him to their "All-America team".<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> He received state-wide honors when he was named "[[Indiana]]'s Mr. Football" later that year.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Residents of his hometown community still remember his accomplishments and passing records. Grossman<U+2019>s high school retired his jersey in the summer of 2007 to commemorate his initial return and success during the [[2006 Chicago Bears|2006 season]].<ref>Sun Sentinel, [http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/sfl-grossman2820070127184105,0,4744849.photo?coll=sfla-sports-front Hoosier state<U+2019>s best] Retrieved on [[February 2]], [[2007]]</ref>

==Collegiate career==
After completing high school, Grossman elected to attend the [[University of Florida]] as opposed to [[Indiana University (Bloomington)|Indiana University]], where his father and grandfather played football.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> After [[Redshirt freshman|redshirting his freshman year]], Grossman became Florida<U+2019>s third string quarterback, behind [[Jesse Palmer]] and [[Brock Berlin]]. Grossman struggled during his first game as the Gators' starting quarterback. After being called to fill in for the injured Palmer, Grossman threw three interceptions against the [[University of Georgia]], prompting coach [[Steve Spurrier]] to bench him in favor of Berlin. Grossman rebounded during the following week by completing 21 of 34 passes for 334 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>Alligator.org, [http://www.alligator.org/edit/issues/00-fall/001106/d02grossman6.htm Grossman rebounds with solid game] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref>

Grossman continued his success by leading the Gators to a 10-2 season in [[2001]]. He came in second to [[University of Nebraska]] quarterback [[Eric Crouch]] in one of the closest votes in [[Heisman Trophy]] history, losing only by 62 votes.<ref>Sports Illustrated, [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/2001/heisman/news/2001/12/08/closer_look/  Bizarre voting robs Grossman of Heisman Trophy] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref>The closest voting was in [[1985]], when [[Auburn University]]'s [[Bo Jackson]] beat [[Chuck Long]] of [[Iowa]] by 16 points. He also earned accolades as the AP National Player-of-the-Year, and finalist for other awards, including the Walter Camp National Player-of-the-Year Award, Maxwell College Player-of-the-Year Award and Davey O'Brien National Quarterback-of-the-Year Award.<ref name="Grossman_ChiSports">Chicago Tribune, [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/cs-2006bearsqnagrossman,1,1349117.htmlstory?coll=cs-home-headlines 20 Questions with Rex Grossman] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref><ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Grossman played in the famed "Slingin' in the Rain" game against [[Louisiana State University]], where he threw 22 completions in 32 attempts, for 464 yards and 5 touchdowns, en route to a 44-15 victory over the Tigers.
<ref>St. Petersburg Times, [http://www.sptimes.com/2002/09/22/Columns/Rex_is_slingin__in_th.shtml Rex is slingin' in the rain] Retrived on [[May 13]], [[2007]]</ref><ref>LSU Athletics, [http://www.lsusports.net/src/data/lsu/assets/docs/fb/01stats/ls04.htm?SPSID=27815&SPID=2164&DB_OEM_ID=5200  Univ. of Florida vs LSU (Oct 06, 2001)] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> In 2006, in an interview with the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', Grossman claimed the victory to be his most memorable game at the University of Florida.<ref name="Grossman_ChiSports">Chicago Tribune, [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/cs-2006bearsqnagrossman,1,1349117.htmlstory?coll=cs-home-headlines 20 Questions with Rex Grossman] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> He ended his sophomore season with a 56-23 victory over the [[Maryland Terrapins football|University of Maryland]] in the 2002 [[Orange Bowl (game)|Orange Bowl]].<ref>CNNSI.com, [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/recaps/2002/01/02/mmd_ffa/  Florida 56, Maryland 23] Retrieved on [[February 26]], [[2007]]</ref>

Grossman completed his junior year by leading the Gators to the 2003 [[Outback Bowl]], where the [[University of Michigan]] defeated the team, 38-30. Nevertheless, he completed 21-of-41 passing for 323 yards and two touchdowns.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Under the helm of [[Ron Zook]], [[Steve Spurrier]]'s successor, Grossman decided to forego his final year of collegiate eligibility and declared for the [[NFL draft]]. Grossman achieved many feats during his collegiate career, including either breaking or approaching many of the records set by [[Danny Wuerffel]], and earned a 146.77 [[passer rating]], becoming the third most efficient passer in the [[Southeastern Conference]]'s history.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Bio">RexGrossman.com, [http://www.rexgrossman.com/profile.htm Rex Grossman #8] Retrieved [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> He also threw 77 touchdowns for 9,164 yards.<ref name="Grossman<U+2019>s_Gators">University of Florida Athletics, [http://www.gatorzone.com/football/bios.php?year=2002&bio=grossman.html University of Florida Athletics: Rex Grossman] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]}}</ref>

==Professional career==
===Early setbacks===
The [[Chicago Bears]] selected Grossman during the first round of the [[2003 NFL Draft]]. Under the leadership of coach [[Dick Jauron]], Grossman was sidelined in favor of veteran quarterbacks [[Chris Chandler]] and [[Kordell Stewart]].<ref>CBC News, [http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2004/03/04/stewart040304.html Bombers eye Kordell Stewart] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Grossman only saw playing time during the later portion of the season after the Bears had been eliminated from playoff contention. His season ended when he was forced to leave the final game with a broken finger.<ref>BearsHistory.com, [http://www.bearshistory.com/seasons/2003chicagobears.aspx Bears History: 2003 Chicago Bears] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Prior to the start of the [[2004 NFL season]], the Bears fired Jauron and hired [[Lovie Smith]], who declared Grossman the team's starting quarterback. Grossman was criticized when he threw a game-ending interception against the Detroit Lions on opening day.<ref>DetroitLions.com, [http://www.detroitlions.com/document_display.cfm?document_id=354549 Big Plays Help Lions Defeat Bears In Opener, Snap Road Losing Streak] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Criticism of his durability intensified when he damaged his knee [[ligaments]] while scrambling for a touchdown against the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in the [[Metrodome]]. The injury forced Grossman to spend the remainder of the season recuperating.<ref>Chicago Suntimes, [http://www.suntimes.com/sports/football/bears/154890,CST-SPT-bear30.article Rex barks, Vikings bite] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref>

Grossman missed most of the [[2005 NFL season]] after breaking his ankle in a pre-season game. Grossman appeared in a press conference after the game, where he remarked, <U+201C>[[Shit happens]]<U+201D> to a crowd of spectators.<ref>BearsHistory.com, [http://www.bearshistory.com/seasons/2005chicagobears.aspx Bears History: 2005 Chicago Bears] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> On [[December 18]], [[2005]], Grossman returned to the field, leading the Bears to a 16-3 victory over the [[Atlanta Falcons]]. In the following game against the [[Green Bay Packers]], he completed eleven of sixteen passes for 166 yards for a touchdown and one interception in a 24-17 victory. Grossman<U+2019>s victory enabled the Bears to clinch a playoff berth and the [[National Football Conference]]'s second playoff seed.<ref>Yahoo! Sports, [http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap;_ylt=Aiv.paelc6d7vB7XjowJKxz.uLYF?gid=20051225009 Chicago 24, Green Bay 17] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> In his first playoff game, Grossman struggled to anchor the Bears<U+2019> offense, throwing 17 of 41 passes for 192 yards for one touchdown and an interception in a 29-21 loss against the [[Carolina Panthers]].<ref>Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, [http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4196/is_20060116/ai_n16004912 NFC DIVISIONAL PLAYOFF: PANTHERS 29 BEARS 21] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref>

===Return===
During the [[2006 Chicago Bears season]], Grossman became the first Bears<U+2019> quarterback to start sixteen games since [[Erik Kramer]] in [[1995 Chicago Bears season|1995]].<ref>ChicagoBears.com, [http://www.chicagobears.com/news/NewsStory.asp?story_id=2859 Grossman closing in on personal milestone] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref> In a season dubbed as a "[[roller coaster]] ride" by Grossman himself, the fourth-year quarterback had several productive performances, which were seemingly diluted by a handful of turnover-ridden games.<ref name="Grossman_06">Chicago Tribune, [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/cs-061220haugh,1,6567579.column Why Tony Romo?] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref> While earning a [[passer rating]] of at least 100 in seven games, he earned a sub 50 rating in five games during the latter portion of the season. Grossman, who was named as the <U+201C>[[National Football Conference|NFC]] Offensive Player of the Month<U+201D> in [[September]], concluded the season<U+2019>s final month with a 64.4 passer rating, including a zero rating during the season<U+2019>s finale game against the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref>Viking View, [http://thevikingview.blogspot.com/2006/09/grossman-nfc-offensive-player-of-month.html Grossman NFC Offensive Player Of The Month] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref><ref>ChicagoBears.com, [http://www.chicagobears.com/news/NewsStory.asp?story_id=2874 Grossman vows to 'fight my way out' after clunker] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref> Grossman<U+2019>s work ethic drew criticism, when he admitted that he was not adequately prepared to play, and later claimed the game to be "meaningless".<ref>ESPN, [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2720086 Grossman says preparation was lacking against Pack] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref> After noticing that his words had been misinterpreted, he rationalized his statement days later.<ref>Chicago Tribune, [http://blogs.chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/rosenblog/2007/01/so_rex_was_misq.html So Rex was misquoted] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref> His inconsistent performance drew criticism, and calls for [[Lovie Smith]] to bench Grossman in favor of the newly acquired veteran [[Brian Griese]].<ref>Chicago Tribune, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/chi-0612110143dec11,1,5349796.story?coll=chi-sportsnew-hed   Grossman's last fling as starter?] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref>

Nevertheless, Smith, who supported Grossman throughout the season, declared that Grossman would remain the Bears<U+2019> starting quarterback throughout the playoffs<ref>[http://www.chicagobears.com/news/NewsStory.asp?story_id=2877 Smith feels Bears are primed for playoffs] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref>, causing much skepticism within the Chicago area.<ref>Chicago Tribune, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/illinois/chi-ap-il-bearsfans,1,5149040.story Chicago Bears fans skeptical after poor play against the Packers] Retrieved on [[January 12]], [[2007]]</ref> He temporarily silenced his critics by leading the Bears to a 27-24 victory over the [[Seattle Seahawks]], completing 21 of 38 passes for 282 yards and one [[interception]], [[fumble]], and touchdown.<ref>ChicagoBears.com, [http://www.chicagobears.com/news/NewsStory.asp?story_id=2922 Bears prevail in OT, one win from Super Bowl] Retrieved on [[January 15]], [[2007]]</ref>  The following week, he led the Bears to 39-14 victory over the [[New Orleans Saints]], which allowed the Bears<U+2019> to claim the [[NFC Championship]] and advance to [[Super Bowl XLI]].<ref>Yahoo! Sports, [http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap;_ylt=Ah20Hvo9GZRY3X_tBs_RaFFDubYF?gid=20070121003 Super Bowl reshuffle: Bears back on top of NFC] Retrieved on [[January 21]], [[2007]] </ref> Grossman completed 20 of 28 passes, including a one-yard touchdown pass. However, he later threw two interceptions, including one that was returned for a touchdown, and fumbled twice due twice due to miscues between him and [[Center (American football)|center]] [[Olin Kreutz]].<ref>Yahoo! Sports, [http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap?gid=20070204003 Indianapolis 29, Chicago 17] Retrieved on [[February 4]], [[2007]]</ref> Despite additional criticism from his detractors, Grossman received the Ed Block Courage Award after the season ended. The award is award to one player from every team, who possesses ideal characteristics of [[sportsmanship]], spirituality, and professionalism, and is believed to be positive [[role model]]s to their community.<ref>ChicagoBears.com, [http://www.chicagobears.com/news/NewsStory.asp?story_id=3157 Grossman to receive prestigious award] Retrieved on [[March 12]], [[2007]].</ref>

==Playing style==
Grossman<U+2019>s [[Gunslinger (American football)|gunslinger]] attitude is illustrated in his desire to throw long passes, similar to his youth mentor, [[Brett Favre]].<ref>NBC Sports, [http://www.nbcsports.com/collinsworth/136291/detail.html Collinsworth mailbag: Grossman reminiscent of Favre] Retrieved on [[January 29]], [[2007]]</ref><ref>Chicago Tribune, [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/cs-061230morrissey,1,1028246.column?coll=cs-home-utility Grossman could be a Favre in training] Retrieved on [[January 29]], [[2007]]</ref> During the 2006 season, Grossman had an above average completion rate when throwing passes worth twenty or more yards, but struggled to complete shorter passes. This attitude attributed to Grossman<U+2019>s inconsistent play.<ref>Yahoo! Sports, [http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=dothebearshaveaprayer&prov=tsn&type=lgns|title=Do the Bears have a prayer?] Retrieved on [[January 29]], [[2007]]</ref> During week twelve of the 2006 season, Grossman threw a game-ending interception while attempting a deep pass to [[Rashied Davis]].<ref>ChicagoBears.com, [http://www.chicagobears.com/news/NewsStory.asp?story_id=2726 Smith's faith in Grossman not wavering] Retrieved on [[January 29]], [[2007]]</ref> However, during the [[National Football League playoffs, 2006-07|Divisional Game of the 2006 Playoffs]], he threw a 68-yard touchdown pass to [[Bernard Berrian]] on the opening play of the Bears<U+2019> second drive.<ref>Washington Post, [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/15/AR2007011500926.html Saints Impressed With Resilient Rex] Retrieved on [[January 29]], [[2007]]</ref>

Additionally, Grossman<U+2019>s ability to elude pursuers and [[scramble]] has significantly decreased since his season ending leg injury in [[2004]].<ref name="rams">Chicago Tribune, [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/cs-061211haugh,1,6502043.column?coll=cs-home-headlines Grossman zeroed in] Retrieved on [[January 29]], [[2007]]</ref> Although he only played three games in 2004, Grossman amassed more rushing yards than he did in sixteen games in 2006.<ref name="allstat">Pro Football Reference, [http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/GrosRe00.htm Rex Grossman Statistics] Retrieved on [[February 24]], [[2007]]</ref> However, he showed his potential to scramble during a game against the [[St. Louis Rams]], after he converted a third and long with a twenty-two yard run. Though the run was the longest of Grossman<U+2019>s career, it only gave him zero net yards for the season at that point.<ref name="rams">Chicago Tribune, [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/cs-061211haugh,1,6502043.column?coll=cs-home-headlines Grossman zeroed in] Retrieved on [[January 29]], [[2007]]</ref>

==Personal life==
Grossman's family has a rich football history. His father and grandfather were football players for [[Indiana University]]. His grandfather, Rex, also played for the [[Baltimore Colts]] during the [[1940]]s.<ref name="Grossman_SunTimes">[Chicago Suntimes, http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4155/is_20031214/ai_n12519557 BEARS' RX: REX Grossman has Spent a Lifetime BEING GROOMED FOR] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> He resides in Bloomington, Indiana during the offseason with his wife Alison Miska, whom he has been married to since [[July 9]], [[2005]].<ref>DaBearz.com, [http://www.dabearz.com/forums/showthread.php?t=2811 Grossman excited about progress with new offense] Retrieved on [[December 24]], [[2006]]</ref> Grossman also has a sister and nephew who live in [[Lincolnwood, Illinois]], a suburb of [[Chicago]]. Also, his parents are friends with [[Archie Manning]], an ex-[[New Orleans Saints]] quarterback and the father of [[Peyton Manning|Peyton]] and [[Eli Manning]].<ref>Chicago Tribune, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/chi-0612130271dec13,1,7905706.story Archie Manning feels for Grossman] Retrieved on [[February 6]], [[2007]]</ref>

Despite the bitter [[Significant rivalries in the NFL|Bears-Packers Rivalry]], Grossman has been a longtime admirer of [[Green Bay Packers]] quarterback [[Brett Favre]] and former Bears quarterback [[Jim Harbaugh]].<ref name="Grossman_ChiSports">Chicago Tribune,  [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/cs-2006bearsqnagrossman,1,1349117.htmlstory?coll=cs-home-headlines   20 Questions with Rex Grossman] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Grossman was also an avid [[Indianapolis Colts]] and [[Indiana Pacers]] fan. Outside of football, he enjoys playing [[basketball]] and watching movies.<ref name="Grossman_ChiSports">Chicago Tribune,  [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/cs-2006bearsqnagrossman,1,1349117.htmlstory?coll=cs-home-headlines   20 Questions with Rex Grossman] Retrieved on [[December 21]]], [[2006]]</ref> Additionally, he is a regular guest on [[WFLD|FOX News Chicago<U+2019>s]] ''The Final Word'', a Sunday night sports show that is co-hosted by former Bears' [[wide receiver]] [[Tom Waddle]]. He also appeared on the cover of ''[[Sports Illustrated]] for Kids''' [[February 2007]] issue. The cover featured Grossman with teammates [[Devin Hester]] and [[Tommie Harris]] posing with [[Bears]] in a [[museum]] exhibit.

Grossman has also earned several [[nickname]]s over the course of his football career.  While at the [[University of Florida]], head coach [[Steve Spurrier]] dubbed him <U+201C>Sexy Rexy." The nickname earned national recognition when teammate [[Muhsin Muhammad]] used the nickname while introducing Grossman during a starting line-up segment on ''[[ESPN Monday Night Football]]''.<ref>Chicago Tribune, [http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/cs-061016bearwithus,1,5761720.column?coll=cs-home-headlines Bear with Us] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref> Grossman was also infamously known as <U+201C>Rex Glassman<U+201D> and <U+201C>Wrecks Grossman<U+201D> due to his injury-prone years.<ref>JSonline.com, [http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=493639 Grossman, Favre both face scrutiny] Retrieved on [[December 21]], [[2006]]</ref>

== NFL career statistics==
The following is a list of Grossman's statistics from his regular and post-season games. Grossman has occasionally put up notable statistics; among all quarterbacks during the [[2006 NFL season]], Grossman ranked tenth in number of pass attempts, seventh in touchdowns thrown, and third in interceptions.<ref name="allstat">Pro Football Reference, [http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/GrosRe00.htm Rex Grossman Statistics] Retrieved on [[February 24]], [[2007]]</ref> He completed his first full season with a relatively low 73.9 [[quarterback rating]]. His supporters have pointed out that this was better than quarterback ratings of [[Brett Favre]], [[Peyton Manning]], and [[Terry Bradshaw]] during their first full seasons;<ref>MidwestBusiness.com, [http://www.midwestbusiness.com/news/viewnews.asp?newsletterID=16500 Reporter<U+2019>s Notebook: The Numbers Don<U+2019>t Lie at RexGrossman.com] Retrieved on [[February 10]], [[2007]]</ref> however, many quarterbacks with relatively undistinguished careers have performed similarly or better in their first years, including Grossman's backup [[Brian Griese]].<ref>NFL.com,  [http://www.nfl.com/players/playerpage/12409 Player Profile - Brian Griese], Retrieved on [[June 19]], [[2007]]</ref> His twenty-three touchdowns in one season rank Grossman among the best Bears quarterbacks in the franchise<U+2019>s history.<ref name="hist">BearsHistory.com, [http://www.bearshistory.com/seasons/2006chicagobears.aspx Bears History: 2006 Chicago Bears] Retrieved on [[March 11]], [[2007]].</ref> However, his twenty interceptions in one season are among the most thrown by any Bears<U+2019> quarterback in almost two decades.<ref name="hist"/> The unusual combination ranked Grossman as statistically the most inconsistent quarterback in almost a decade, just ahead of [[Ben Roethlisberger]].<ref>Pro Football Reference, [http://www.pro-football-reference.com/blog/wordpress/?p=228 Rex Grossman] Retrieved on [[March 11]], [[2007]].</ref>

